<br>
The bad examples are precisely the reasons for judging against religions in general.<br>
<br>
And regardless if there ever were a ressurrection, basing a religion upon the death and sacrafice is (IMO) wrong.  If he knew he was the son of god, then he knew he wasn't really dying, hence he didn't sacrafice anything.  This is a huge hole in Christianity that has never been filled.<br>
<br>
I personally believe that the story of christ is fiction.  There are way too many inconsistencies, loopholes, and missing outside validation to support the story.  Even the gospels greatly contradict each other in their tone and representation of their story.<br>
<br>
Bad fiction, existing to this day because people were killed if they didn't believe. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/utoekpet966.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Toekpet966</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 71<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/7/02 11:41 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm24.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=684>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> b</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I believe it takes more faith to NOT believe in God.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
to an extent, I beleive this can be <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> very</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> true... religion really <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> does</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> answer everything in a world that dosn't hold enough 'physical answers'. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/utoekpet966.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Toekpet966</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 72<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/7/02 12:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm24.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=685>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> b</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  here is an excerpt from my essay about a book &quot;Something Wicked This Way Comes&quot;(read this book if you already haven't). We were supposed to write about the theme of &quot;forbidden power&quot;... I believe this is somewhat appropriate to the subject at hand.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Power, in any form of course, does not appear out of thin air. Something must give fuel. I believe that the carousel was fueled--and this is important--by the fear of death. Fear.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Death doesn't exist, it never will. But we've drawn so many pictures of it, so many years trying to pin it down, comprehend it, we've got to thinking of it as an entity, strangely alive and greedy. All it is, however, is a stopped watch, a loss, an end, a darkness. Nothing (p 150- 151)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
All animals , including humans (<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> homo sapiens</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, we're animals too), have a built in instinct of self-preservation. We don't want to die, but we <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> all</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> do. It's one of the many predicaments humans find themselves in, end. I think the carnivals <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> forbidden power</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of death, is a lot like the power of death that organized religion possesses.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> And, Will thought, here comes the carnival, Death like a rattle in one hand, Life like candy in the other, shake one to scare you, offer one to make your mouth water. Here comes the side show, both hands <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> full</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->! (p 100) <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Hell like rattle in one hand, heaven like candy in the other... offer one to make your mouth water. Fear. I think the things that make man succumb to religion are the same things that made people ride the carousel [that made people younger in this story]. A hole exists that needs to be filled, with some more life, with peace, with order--security. Death is this hole, this nothing. Eternal nothing, nameless, undefined, it is the greatest fear because it is existent and not, nothing more implausible can be given to our human minds than the minds' own end! Ponder that--one day you will be no more... can you conceive it? <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Inexistence</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->--does it <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> exist</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. No matter what, it seems, we are not capable of accepting death in its entirety, and so in life we create fountains of youth, carousels of time, eternal souls... gods, heavens and hells. Real or not, these things affect us to the bone. All of which are forbidden powers. Manipulating a simple insecurity of man, a simple insecurity that is man's greatest downfall. There doesn't have to be a carousel, the plain idea of one is forbidden enough. Ideas are everything, imaginations are everything. Humans do not perceive the great world of meaningless nothing around us for what it is, but rather we machinate our own little synthetic view of reality, aside from what our nerves, eyes, and ears experience. Sentiments, perspectives, they are all complete and final truth to the beholder. If you believe in god--there is god. If you believe in heaven--there is a heaven. But most importantly--believe it or not--there is death. Ignore it, forget it, brush it off or be overwhelmed by it... it won't go away until you do with it. I like and completely agree with how this book tells us to laugh death off.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  &quot;Death's funny, God damn it!...&quot; (p 210) <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
It's funny. Death, the question without an answer, the question that shouldn't be asked but always is. The only way to fight back is with laughter. You can't reasonably hit death head-on! Death isn't reasonable! Death is a hole in reason, we want it filled--and it can't be. So it's your choice: laugh or cry because you live and die. Mr. Halloway explains it best in a morale raising episode with his son Will at a time when Jim is getting sucked in by the clutches of sorrow and into death, and they must save him. Why we must laugh:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> &quot;Damn it, Willy, all this, all these, Mr Dark and his sort, they <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> like</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> crying, my God, they <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> love</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> tears! Jesus God, the more you bawl, the more they drink the salt off your chin, Wail and they suck your breath like cats. Get up! Get off your knees damn it! Jump around! Whoop and holler! You hear! Shout, Will, sing, but most of all laugh, you got that, laugh!&quot; (p 208 ) <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
The fuel that stimulated human weakness into human strength, versus the idea of death, was laughter. Laughter overcame a forbidden power--suddenly not so forbidden and morbidly daunting when looked at from a comical angle. The following quote contains the thoughts of Mr. Halloway as the witch was killing him<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Somehow, irresistibly, the prime thing was: nothing mattered. Life in end seemed a prank of such size you could only stand off at this end of the corridor to note its meaningless length and its quite unnecessary height, a mountain built to such ridiculous immensities you were dwarfed in its shadow and mocking of its pomp. So with death near he thought numbly but purely upon a billion vanities, arrivals, departures, idiot excursions of boy, boy-man, man and old man goat. He had gathered and stacked all manner of foibles, devices, play things of his egotism and now, between all the silly corridors of books, the toys of his life swayed. And none more grotesque than this thing named Witch Gypsy Reader-of-Dust, tickling, that's what! just <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> tickling</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the air! Fool! Didn't she know what she was <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> doing!</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->! ( p 169 ) <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Laugh them all away~! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/uyoshamendel.showPublicProfile?language=EN>YoshaMendel</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 98<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/8/02 8:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm24.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=686>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.geocities.com/arvcondor/radioactivejewman.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: b</span><hr size=1> wow i cant beleive this forum actually went to page 2. first time in what, 4 months? <p><img src="http://www.geocities.com/arvcondor/dalarr.jpg"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/utoekpet966.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Toekpet966</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 76<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/8/02 9:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm24.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=687>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> t</span><hr size=1> and to keep it going try to respond someones post.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/uanywon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Anywon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Contributing Member</span><br>  Posts: 382<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/11/02 12:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm24.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=688>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: t</span><hr size=1> Use this thread instead of starting a n